  "prompt": "What colleges can I get into with a 4.8 weighted GPA and 2130 SAT score?",
  "response": "With a weighted GPA of 4.8 and a SAT score of 2130, you are likely in a strong position for admission to many competitive colleges and universities. However, admission decisions also depend on a range of other factors, including the rigor of your coursework, extracurricular activities, letters of recommendation, personal essays, and demographic factors. \n\nHere\u2019s a general breakdown of types of colleges you might consider:\n\n### Highly Competitive Schools:\n1. **Ivy League Schools:** Harvard, Yale, Princeton, Columbia, etc.\n2. **MIT and Stanford:** Top-tier tech and research universities.\n3. **Selective Public Universities:** University of California\u2014Berkeley, UCLA, University of Michigan, University of Virginia.\n\n### Competitive Schools:\n1. **Top Public Universities:** University of North Carolina\u2014Chapel Hill, University of Florida, University of Wisconsin\u2014Madison.\n2. **Private Universities:** Boston College, University of Southern California, Brandeis University.\n\n### Regional and Less Selective Schools:\n1. Many reputable state universities and liberal arts colleges will also be very accessible with your academic profile.\n\n### Tips for the Application Process:\n- **Check Specific Requirements:** Each college has its own admission criteria, including the importance of GPA and standardized test scores.\n- **Look at Holistic Admission Processes:** Many schools take a holistic approach, meaning they value personal qualities and achievements alongside academic metrics.\n- **Consider Early Decision/Early Action:** This can sometimes improve your chances of admission at certain institutions.\n- **Extracurricular Activities:** Engage in meaningful activities that reflect your interests and leadership potential.\n\nMake sure to research each school's admission profile, trends, and selectivity to find the best fit for you. Good luck!",
